{
  "texts": [
    "As a result, authorship does not depend only on person or technology or science itself for that matter but to the relations between those.",
    "But before we engage further with these arguments, we need to see how the concept of authorship developed throughout the history.",
    "In antiquity, authorship was often a collective endeavor, with works being attributed to cultural heroes or gods (Foley 1985).",
    "The Homeric epics, for instance, were part of an oral tradition and only later attributed to a singular figure, Homer (Lord 2003).",
    "In this period, the emphasis was on the communal transmission of knowledge and stories, and the concept of individual authorship was less prominent (Nagy 1996)."
  ]
}